ituitarism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GH, LH, FSH, TSH, ACTH","LH, FSH, TSH, ACTH, GH","FSH, GH, LH, TSH, ACTH","GH, LH, FSH, ACTH, TSH","ACTH, TSH, FSH, LH, GH"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn progressive hypopituitarism, hormone deficiencies typically develop in a predictable sequence, listed from first to last:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone (GH)\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGonadotropins (\u003Cstrong\u003Eluteinizing hormone (LH)\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)\u003C/strong\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis sequence reflects the differential sensitivity of distinct pituitary cell populations to injury or compression. Understanding this pattern is crucial for monitoring patients with developing hypopituitarism and initiating appropriate hormone replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Growth hormone is typically the first hormone to be affected in progressive hypopituitarism","The sequence of hormone loss in hypopituitarism is generally: GH \u2192 LH/FSH \u2192 TSH \u2192 ACTH","Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) is usually the last to be affected in progressive hypopituitarism"],"references":["Kim SY. Diagnosis and Treatment of Hypopituitarism. Endocrinol Metab (Seoul). 2015 Dec;30(4):443-55. doi: 10.3803/EnM.2015.30.4.443. PMID: 26790380; PMCID: PMC4722397","Beysel S, \u00c7ali\u015fkan M, Kizilg\u00fcl M, Kan S, \u00d6zbek M, \u00c7akal E. Clinical evaluation of pituitary insufficiency in adult population. Turk J Med Sci. 2020 Jun 23;50(4):917-921. doi: 10.3906/sag-1908-19. PMID: 32283895; PMCID: PMC7379402"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15619"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56634"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T15:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T15:44:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8310"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":